      "text": "<h3> Warming Up to Enriched Category Theory, Part 2</h3>\n<p>Thu, Jun 17, 2021</p>\n<p>Let's jump right in to where we left off in part 1 of our warm-up to enriched category theory. If you'll recall from last time, we saw that the set of truth values $\\{0, 1\\}$ and the unit interval $[0,1]$ and the nonnegative extended reals $[0,\\infty]$ were not just sets but actually preorders and hence categories. We also hinted at the idea that a \"category enriched over\" one of these preorders (whatever that means &#148; we hadn't defined it yet!) looks something like a collection of objects $X,Y,\\ldots$ where there is at most one arrow between any pair $X$ and $Y$, and where that arrow can further be \"decorated with\" &#148;or simply replaced by &#148; a number from one of those three exemplary preorders.With that background in mind, my goal in today's article is to say exactly what a category enriched over a preorder is- [https://www.math3ma.com/blog/warming-up-to-enriched-category-theory-part-2 math3ma.com]</p>\n<hr>"
