      "text": "<h3> Operator Norm, Intuitively</h3>\n<p>Fri, Nov 23, 2018</p>\n<p>If $X$ and $Y$ are normed vector spaces, a linear map $T:X\\to Y$ is said to be <b>bounded</b> if $\\|T\\|&lt; \\infty$ where $$\\|T\\|=\\sup_{\\underset{x\\neq 0}{x\\in X}}\\left\\{\\frac{|T(x)|}{|x|}\\right\\}.$$ (Note that $|T(x)|$ is the norm in $Y$ whereas $|x|$ is the norm in $X$.) One can show that this is equivalent to $$\\|T\\|=\\sup_{x\\in X}\\{|T(x)|:|x|=1\\}.$$ So intuitively (at least in two dimensions), we can think of $\\|T\\|$ this way&brvbar;- [https://www.math3ma.com/blog/operator-norm-intuitively math3ma.com]</p>\n<hr>"
